{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"language":"python","display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.12.12","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Edge AI Optimization: Post-Training INT8 Quantization with MobileNetV2\n\n**Objective:** Deploying deep learning models on edge devices (like microcontrollers, IoT devices, or mobile phones) requires strict memory and compute efficiency. This project demonstrates a complete edge-ML pipeline:\n1. Building a lightweight image classifier using transfer learning (MobileNetV2).\n2. Exporting a standard Float32 baseline model.\n3. Applying Post-Training INT8 Quantization to compress the model.\n4. Benchmarking the quantized model to prove significant storage reduction (~70%) with minimal accuracy loss.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 1. Environment Setup\nFirst, we import native TensorFlow. Instead of relying on high-level wrapper APIs which often suffer from dependency conflicts in modern Python environments, we will build the TFLite conversion pipeline from scratch.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import os\nimport numpy as np\nimport tensorflow as tf\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\nprint(f\"TensorFlow Version: {tf.__version__}\")","metadata":{"_uuid":"8f2839f25d086af736a60e9eeb907d3b93b6e0e5","_cell_guid":"b1076dfc-b9ad-4769-8c92-a6c4dae69d19","trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-01T18:53:47.388463Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-01T18:53:47.389295Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-01T18:53:47.393630Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-01T18:53:47.389262Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-01T18:53:47.392897Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"TensorFlow Version: 2.19.0\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":37},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 2. Fetching the Dataset\nWe will use the standard TensorFlow Flower dataset for this demonstration. It contains 5 classes of flowers and is diverse enough to test the model's feature extraction capabilities.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"dataset_url = \"https://storage.googleapis.com/download.tensorflow.org/example_images/flower_photos.tgz\"\ndata_dir = tf.keras.utils.get_file('flower_photos', origin=dataset_url, untar=True)\nprint(f\"Dataset downloaded to: {data_dir}\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-01T18:53:47.402406Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-01T18:53:47.402731Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-01T18:53:50.045914Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-01T18:53:47.402707Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-01T18:53:50.045113Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Dataset downloaded to: /root/.keras/datasets/flower_photos\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":38},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 3. Data Pipeline Preparation\nWe use `image_dataset_from_directory` to create efficient `tf.data.Dataset` objects. We also resize all images to 224x224, which is the standard input size expected by the MobileNetV2 architecture.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"BATCH_SIZE = 32\nIMG_SIZE = (224, 224)\n\n# Load Training Data\ntrain_ds = tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(\n  data_dir,\n  validation_split=0.2,\n  subset=\"training\",\n  seed=123,\n  image_size=IMG_SIZE,\n  batch_size=BATCH_SIZE\n)\n\n# Load Validation Data\nval_ds = tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(\n  data_dir,\n  validation_split=0.2,\n  subset=\"validation\",\n  seed=123,\n  image_size=IMG_SIZE,\n  batch_size=BATCH_SIZE\n)\n\nclass_names = train_ds.class_names\nprint(f\"Classes: {class_names}\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-01T18:53:50.047592Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-01T18:53:50.047934Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-01T18:53:50.306830Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-01T18:53:50.047908Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-01T18:53:50.306210Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Found 3670 files belonging to 1 classes.\nUsing 2936 files for training.\nFound 3670 files belonging to 1 classes.\nUsing 734 files for validation.\nClasses: ['flower_photos']\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":39},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 4. Transfer Learning Architecture\nTo create an efficient edge model, we use **MobileNetV2** pre-trained on ImageNet. We freeze the base model's weights to retain its feature extraction abilities and attach a custom dense layer to classify our specific 5 flower classes. \n*Note: I will include a rescaling layer directly inside the model to ensure inputs are automatically normalized to the `[-1, 1]` range expected by MobileNetV2.*","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"preprocess_input = tf.keras.layers.Rescaling(1./127.5, offset=-1)\n\n# Load the base model pre-trained on ImageNet\nbase_model = tf.keras.applications.MobileNetV2(\n    input_shape=IMG_SIZE + (3,),\n    include_top=False,\n    weights='imagenet'\n)\nbase_model.trainable = False # Freeze the base model\n\n# Build the final model\nmodel = tf.keras.Sequential([\n  tf.keras.Input(shape=IMG_SIZE + (3,)),\n  preprocess_input,\n  base_model,\n  tf.keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D(),\n  tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),\n  tf.keras.layers.Dense(len(class_names), activation='softmax')\n])\n\nmodel.compile(\n    optimizer='adam',\n    loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',\n    metrics=['accuracy']\n)\nmodel.summary()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-01T18:53:50.307702Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-01T18:53:50.307940Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-01T18:53:51.721189Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-01T18:53:50.307908Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-01T18:53:51.720656Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"\u001b[1mModel: \"